Your first streaming query — a rate source into a memory sink.

Let's build the simplest possible end-to-end streaming query — one that needs no external system at all.

We use two pieces. The rate source generates rows at a fixed rate, with two columns — a timestamp, and a value. And the memory sink collects the results into an in-memory temporary view, which you can then query with sequel.

The write-stream call chains a few things together. Format memory sets the sink type. Query-name registers the results under a name, so you can select from it in sequel. Output-mode append emits new rows only. And start actually launches the query, and returns a streaming-query handle.

Then we call await-termination with five, to let the query run for five seconds, and finally we call stop.

The important thing to notice is that start returns a handle. That handle is how you observe the query, and how you stop it — and observing and controlling that handle is exactly what the next several sections are about.
